            <div class="mainBodyText">
                <span class="fs5"><!-- OldURL: http://boards2.parentsplace.com/messages/get/pplibchristiann9/36/1/1/1.html -->
<p>Job needs better copyright protection against "Unauthorized Derivative Works"...</p>

The core material of Job (3.1 through 31.40 and 38.1 through 42.6) probably date from the sixth or fifth century BCE. They are a pivotal work addressing the problem of evil. Primitive religious thought associates "pleasing God/the gods" with immediate, material rewards. Shamans offer sacrifices with the expectation that some immanent evil will be averted, or some benefit obtained. This is the ethic implied in much of the national histories that precede Job in the Bible: keep the Law, and you will prosper in the land; break the Law and you will be hauled into exile by Babylonians.
<P>

In the light of that accepted orthodoxy; Job's author was the heterodox theist of his time. He takes a traditional folk-tale and turns it into a celebration of the empirical fact, that sometimes good people suffer from so-called "acts of God"; that god-fearing piety does *not* guarantee protection, that the victims are not necessarily *deserving* of some divine punishment. These are themes that we still struggle with; and still, at least 2500 years after Job's authorship, we hear conservative theists arguing that we bring our own suffering upon ourselves, or that God uses misfortune to punish us for our apostacy or to purify from our sins.
<P>

The "Elihu" voice in Job, is the voice of one of those conservative theists coming along a couple hundred years after the original authore: a good orthodox believer who tried to salvage the beautiful poetry of Job without allowing Job's raw challenge to "God's perfect Justice" to stand. In other words, the Elihu passages completely missed the point. And as you say, it is glaringly obvious. It seems suddenly about another theme altogether, because... it is suddenly about another theme altogether. 
<P>

Not to mention that the "Elihu" character shows up out of nowhere, completely without introduction in the book. Did you ever read "fan fiction" of Star Trek or another 'cult' program? It's fairly common for a fan to engage in an episode or story line so intensely that they imagine themselves into the story, sometimes even re-writing the story with their own character in it at the crucial scene. Every time I read the Elihu passages, I think of that genre.
<P>

Of course, what Job is often assumed to be, is chronological history: following Esther as an actual record of events occuring to a real man. And of course, that is completely out of keeping with the style and content of the book. The national histories dealt with the doings and ethics of kings and prophets. In contrast, Job himself is "just this guy, you know?" One could call it "historical fiction", but that underrepresents it. The book (without, of course, the fan-fiction insertions) is highly structured, after the fashion of some classical literature rather than a history: like a Greek Tragedy, perhaps, or like a formal Discourse. I like your analogy to epic poetry. 

<P>

</span>
