            <div class="mainBodyText">
                <span class="fs5"><!-- OldURL: http://boards2.parentsplace.com/messages/get/pplibchristiann9/36/2/2/1.html -->
<p>Oh! Perspicacious woman! This is indeed the crux of the matter...</p>

and the crux of a great many New Testament passages, including the Crux itself!
<P>

The English word "sin" is ancient, coming into English from the Old Norse, and meaning offence, wrong-doing, misdeed. It carries the connotation of intent, and action.
<P>

Jesus introduced the concept that people could "sin" without *doing* anything: by the thoughts we harbour, the words we use, and the deeds we do *not* do. This idea is captured in the  church's ancient 'common confession': "We confess that we have sinned against Thee: in our thoughts and in our words, in what we have done and in what we have left undone."
<P>

This idea of internal, unintentional 'sin' makes sin a much more formidable enemy. It is much more difficult -- perhaps impossible  -- to control our thoughts than to simply control our actions. Many historical Christians have experienced tremendous guilt from passing "sinful" notions flitting through their consciousness. I consider such guilt to be misplaced, and here is why:
<P>

The Greek word that is translated "sin", harmatanos, does not have the same meaning that the Hebrew word "chatta'ah" has. Harmatanos is an archery term, and refers to the distance by which an arrow misses its mark. Archers strive constantly to reduce their "harmatanos". Perhaps Robin Hood could consistently split one grey-goose shaft with another, but real-life archers always have some measurable "grouping" to their shots, and always have at least a little improvement to strive for.
<P>

Over-acheivers often find confidence and security in their own personal power: relying on being the best, being unassailable. Then we come face-to-face with the fact that we are *not* Robin Hood; that we *do* miss the mark by some distance, that we mis-spell silly things in our posts -- that we have sinned and fallen short of the glory of God. At those times, we may be tempted to over-aggrandize our errors; beat our brests, take an unreasonable share of guilt and wallow in it. The author of Psalm 17 has avoided that trap, and walks the very difficult line of plain reasonableness. Without claiming any perfection that he has *not* acheive, he also avoids denigrating his position: he states his case plainly before God as judge. And this is also the message of Job: that we can come before God, face him fearlessly without hubris or belligerence or excessive humility, and trust in God's judgement.

<P>

</span>
                <table><tr></tr></table>
