            <div class="mainBodyText">
                <span class="fs5"><!-- OldURL: http://boards2.parentsplace.com/messages/get/pplibchristiann9/36/2/2/2.html -->
<p>Sin is understood differently in different traditions...</p>

(This is all on top of what Pamela said)
<P>

Some christians don't acknowledge unintended sins and unknown sins. The intent of heart and mind is what counts as wrong. If person#1 intends to good for person#2 and it ends up hurting person#2, person#1 should learn from the experience but it was not sin as it wasn't intentional. Sort of like the difference between manslaughter and murder, there are layers of "should have foreseen" and "should have known better" but no man knows the heart and mind of another so the judgement is left to God.
<P>

In these traditions, the first sin was that a person *decided* to challenge God's authority in deed.  It would have been one thing to consider whether or not God knew all or spoke truth; it was a totally different thing to act on that questioning by disobedience. Setting personal authority above God's authority is sin/separation/fragmentation of unity.
<P>

There were many prophets who disliked speaking and felt compelled to speak out against their nations and leaders but Jonah was punished because he (an acknowledged and active prophet) put his judgement of Ninevah over God's. When he finally spoke to Ninevah and they repented, Jonah AGAIN tried to put his judgement (they deserved to be flattened) over God's judgement (they deserved forgiveness and a second chance).
<P>

In some churches they ask forgiveness for "things done and undone" and leave out "things known and unknown".
<P>

I would (I think) side with the intent people. Do I really need to be foregiven for things that I did wrong that I had and have no idea are wrong? When someone shows or tells me how they are wrong then I'll be sorry and ask for forgiveness but I don't think there are hidden sins. It smacks of hidden knowledge and secret practices and that isn't what my religion is about. It reminds me of a speaker at my high school chapel who claimed that "Bridge over Troubled Water" was a drug culture song and that even if we weren't aware of the implication of the phrases in the song, somehow our subconcious knew that it was a drug song and our souls were damaged and in peril from exposure to the song. I rolled my eyes then and I roll them now. If he hadn't told us what the dubious phrases meant then we would have continued to sing and hear the song as community and support. As it is, I still think he was wrong in his premis, the song was about community, friendship, and support because that is how we sang it and meant it regardless of what the intent of the lyricist.
<P>

Sara

<P>

</span>
