            <br clear="all" />

            <div class="mainBodyText">
                <span class="fs5"><!-- OldURL: http://boards2.parentsplace.com/messages/get/pplibchristiann9/36/2/2/3.html -->
<p>I'm used to the definition of sin as that which separates us from God, (m)</p>

but I don't know about this unintentional sin Pamela mentions.
<P>

First, your question about whether sin is internal or external -- you give an example of being less than noble as external, and conscience as internal.  
<P>

As I understand it, being "less than noble" can manifest itself externally or internally as sin.  Refusing to forgive, or nursing a grudge, are internal, yet less than noble.
<P>

Conscience, though, is an internal sin detection device -- you are supposed to have a properly formed conscience, so you can tell if you've sinned or not.  That doesn't just mean that you feel guilty about everything.  It is possible to have an overly prickly conscience, and the word that I know for that is "scrupulosity."  As the priest explained it to me, "God is not a nit picker."  You are supposed to have a conscience that you can examine and know what is really becoming an obstacle between you and God.  You are not supposed to have a conscience that constantly tells you that you are falling short, because if you feel unworthy all the time you cannot feel peace or thanksgiving, which God intends for us.  
<P>

As far as Pamela's discussion of unknown sin, in my son's sacramental prep classes* this fall, they are very clearly making the distinction between accidents, mistakes, and choices.  As with Sara's examples above, the kids are being taught that it's not a sin to make a mistake or have an accident -- it's a sin to do something on purpose that you know you shouldn't do.  That includes internal issues, (plotting revenge on your little brother), and sins of omission, but it doesn't include "unknown sins".  
<P>

Pamela mentioned that some churches include "known and unknown" sins in the general confession they recite.  The version of that which is said in the Catholic church is "I confess to Almighty God, and to you, my brothers and sisters, that I have sinned, through my own fault, in my thoughts and in my words, in what I have done, and in what I have failed to do.  And I ask Blessed Mary, ever virgin, all the angels and saints, and you, my brothers and sisters, to pray for me to the Lord our God."  That is part of our liturgy.  I don't understand the idea of claiming fault for something you didn't know about.
<P>

* (sacramental prep classes are classes in preparation for the sacramants of reconciliation and eucharist.  Around second grade, catholic kids get ready for those sacraments.  In other churches, things are different, but because we are in the middle of those explanations at my house, I thought I'd mention it.)

<P>

</span>
