            <div class="mainBodyText">
                <span class="fs5"><!-- OldURL: http://boards2.parentsplace.com/messages/get/pplibchristiann9/36/3/1.html -->
<p>A repost from the Anglican board...</p>

The reading from Job inspired Handel to write I Know That My Redeemer Liveth. I love "The Messiah" and have several versions of it although none live up to my memory of my parents 6 record set of the Mormon Tabernacle Choir. The MTC has a new version out but they've jiggled the baritones and it doesn't hold up the standard. While often divided into sections and relegated to Christmas and Easter, The Messiah is appropriate all year round (though one might skip the Alleluia chorus and other Easter portions during Lent). Play "I Know That MY Redeemer Liveth" and talk about the poetry of hope and faith. 
<P>

The Job reading has inspired me to work our oral history into Christmas gifts this year. Kolbe is working on a quilt of her life with milestone squares. I thought we could do more storytelling while putting together photo albums. I'm making photo albums (acid free) with photos for presents and thinking about writing down memories/stories that I am reminded of by some photos. The girls can write down or dictate their stories for the albums as well. 
<P>

Fall is a good time to talk about the apple of your eye (Psalm 17). Some orchards are still allowing pick your own and the local farmers markets have many varieties. Each person could pick the apple that pleases her eye and then there are so many wonderful things to do with the apples (pie, caramel apples, applesauce, baked). The phrase apple of your eye is used several times in the Bible; see how many you can find.(try searching <A HREF="http://www.unboundbible.org/">http://www.unboundbible.org/</A>) 
<P>


<PRE>Why we record also ties in with the prayerbooks we are making. This week we are adding a prayer from the Celtic oral tradition - 1st millennium.
 You are the peace of all things calm.
 You are the place to hide from harm.
 You are the light that shines in dark.
 You are the heart's eternal spark.
 You are the door that's open wide.
 You are the guest who waits inside.
 You are the stranger at the door.
 You are the calling of the poor.
 You are my Lord and with me from ill.
 You are the light, the truth, the way.
 You are my Saviour this very day."</PRE>
<P>

We have been talking about death and afterlife since September 11th. Really, it's an ongoing discussion since my Grandfather died in 1995. I use the Luke reading in connection with our All Saints discussions to talk about the continuity of life and community that goes beyond this flesh and world. 
<P>

II Thessalonians reminds me that we all need pats on the back and praise whether we are sweeping along or slogging through the mire. I'm slogging.
<P>

Sara

<P>

</span>
