            <div class="mainBodyText">
                <span class="fs5"><!-- OldURL: http://boards2.parentsplace.com/messages/get/pplibchristiann9/36/4.html -->
<p>tears into office, flipping back collar while dodging the coffee spilling over my mug and nods coolly at the Boss Lede</p>

...all while mumbling under my breath, "Haggai? Who was Haggai?" According to the NASB:
<P>

Haggai 1:15
on the twenty-fourth day of the sixth month in the second year of Darius the king. 
Haggai 2:1
On the twenty-first of the seventh month, the word of the LORD came by Haggai the prophet saying,
Haggai 2:2
"Speak now to Zerubbabel the son of Shealtiel, governor of Judah, and to Joshua the son of Jehozadak, the high priest, and to the remnant of the people saying,
Haggai 2:3
'Who is left among you who saw this temple in its former glory? And how do you see it now? Does it not seem to you like nothing in comparison?
Haggai 2:4
'But now take courage, Zerubbabel,' declares the LORD, 'take courage also, Joshua son of Jehozadak, the high priest, and all you people of the land take courage,' declares the LORD, 'and work; for I am with you,' declares the LORD of hosts.
Haggai 2:5
'As for the promise which I made you when you came out of Egypt, My Spirit is abiding in your midst; do not fear!'
Haggai 2:6
"For thus says the LORD of hosts, 'Once more in a little while, I am going to shake the heavens and the earth, the sea also and the dry land.
Haggai 2:7
'I will shake all the nations; and they will come with the wealth of all nations, and I will fill this house with glory,' says the LORD of hosts.
Haggai 2:8
'The silver is Mine and the gold is Mine,' declares the LORD of hosts.
Haggai 2:9
'The latter glory of this house will be greater than the former,' says the LORD of hosts, 'and in this place I will give peace,' declares the LORD of hosts."
<P>

Now, what does this mean? And how do we understand it in its historical context? What pearls of wisdom are contained within that have timeless application and can be used today?
<P>

Historically, I wonder if they were being consoled after some really bad times. This is a short book; blurb, really. The footnotes are more contextual, like the date in which it was written (2nd year of Darius' reign, hence 520 BC). The passage asks the people to compare the temple now to what it was during the great reign of Solomon. I get the feeling that there was heavy dispair about its loss of glory and splendor and the words of God are to console the people.
<P>

How can we apply that in today's world? How do we console ourselves when faced with that old paradox: "you can never go home again"? Do we look to God to promise us that glory will return? How do we benefit? Is it not better to remember the splendor of yesterday, but concentrate on building new glories for tomorrow? This is a wistful passage to me.
<P>

*ppssstt, Pam: how did I do?*
<P>

aloha, Luahiwa

<P>

</span>
