            <br clear="all" />

            <div class="mainBodyText">
                <span class="fs5"><!-- OldURL: http://boards2.parentsplace.com/messages/get/pplibchristiann9/36/4/1.html -->
<p>Good work: Some context...</p>

Between 598 and 586 BCE, the Israelites had been deported into exile by the conquering Babylonians (see 2 Kings24.8 through 25.12). In 539 BCE, after the Babylonian empire fell to the Persians, the exile was lifted and some of the Jews returned to Judah (see Ezra chapters 3 and 4). The prophet Haggai was one of these returnees; the entire book of Haggai comprises four short prophecies that Haggai received over three and a half months.
<P>

When the exiles returned to Judea, the Hebrew religion was not re-established immediately, and the Temple was not rebuilt. In his first prophecy, Haggai declares that God would provide economic prosperity as a reward for rebuilding the temple, and withhold economic security from the people if they did not rebuild the temple (in effect, the very opposite theme from Job, the other old-testament option for this Sunday). 
<P>

The assigned reading is the second prophecy, delivered about one month after the returned exiles began rebuilding the temple. It had been 67 years since the destruction of the temple: the oldest of the exiles would have been barely twelve or thirteen when the temple was destroyed; most of those who could remember the "this temple in its former glory" would remember it with the larger-than-life distortion of a toddler's or preschooler's memory; and the vast majority of the exiles would no it only through their parents' and grandparents' stories.
<P>

Did God really want a temple? God never showed any sign of needing a Temple in the early days of Israel's settlement or even during the reign of David (see 2Samual 7.5 and forward); and even when Solomon who did build the temple, it was presented as his idea, not God's (1 Kings 5.5). But, the temple became a symbol of Israel's nationhood. By insisting on the temple, was Haggai offering the returnees a cultural identity that had been stripped from them invasion and cultural genocide? Was this his remedy to the Babylonian policy of cultural integration (which is what their mass deportations were intended to achieve)?
<P>

The promise of "silver and gold", "latter glory greater than former glory", and a "place of peace" were the promise of everything the returnees lacked -- and felt that they deserved, while those undeserving Jews who chose to live on in the Diaspora enjoyed the relative prosperity that we see illustrated in the Book of Esther. The question of course is, whether these promises came true (one of the tests of a true prophet). And at a material level, they did not. The temple described in 1 Kings 5.5 and forward greatly overshadowed the second temmple; and the "place of peace" was over-run by subsequent armies and destroyed again, and finally again. The domain in which these promises do come true (in Christian thought) is on the spiritual plane: for this is the Temple where our great treasure Christ, the Prince of Peace, taught and drove out the money-changers.
<P>

---------------------------------
<P>

BTW, you did good. I like your thought, that the returnees probably shared that same unachievable yearning for the mythic "home" felt by so many children of the exiled and disenfranchised. We desperately long to give our ancestors back their "former glory" -- and, yes, to claim it for ourselves as well. And we recognise how unrealistic that yearning is. You are right, this is a wistful passage. Thank-you for your insight.

<P>

</span>
